            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ivan Petrov\u2019s story began not in the fog of San Francisco, but in the stark, structured world of 1970s Leningrad. The son of a pragmatic engineer and a librarian, Ivan was a quiet boy who found his voice not in words, but in objects. While his father preached the logic of schematics, Ivan was captivated by the grain of the wood on his grandmother\u2019s dacha furniture and the forbidden magic of a smuggled Beatles album played on a crackling tape deck. The guitar was his revelation\u2014a machine that turned wood and wire into pure emotion.\n\nWith the dissolution of the Soviet Union, a 20-year-old Ivan saw a sliver of opportunity and immigrated to the U.S. in 1994. He landed in the Pacific Northwest, drawn by its forests. He enrolled in a fine woodworking program at a community college in Oregon, where his innate talent for precision and form flourished. A turning point came when he repaired a fellow student\u2019s broken guitar neck, feeling a profound connection to the instrument\u2019s revival. He realized he didn't just want to build things; he wanted to build voices. He apprenticed for years under an old, cantankerous luthier in Portland, absorbing every secret of wood selection, bracing, and French polishing.\n\nIn the early 2000s, Ivan moved to San Francisco, drawn by its legendary music scene and artistic soul. He opened \"Petrov Guitars,\" a small, unassuming shop in the Mission District. Today, his life is a rhythm of craft. His 4.8-mile bicycle commute from his small apartment in a quieter part of Bernal Heights is his morning meditation, a physical climb that clears his mind. His days are spent in a sanctuary fragrant with sawdust, lacquer, and old wood, meticulously restoring vintage Martins or crafting his own exquisite acoustic guitars. His clientele consists of dedicated local musicians and serious collectors who value his old-world skill in a city obsessed with the new.\n\nIvan remains a private man, his social life revolving around a few fellow artisans and the musicians who have become friends. He\u2019s a fixture at local folk shows, always watching the player's hands. At 49, Ivan has no grand ambitions for expansion or wealth. His dream is to continue his craft, to feel the resonance of a perfect instrument under his hands, and perhaps, to find a deserving apprentice to whom he can pass on his knowledge. For Ivan, success isn't a stock option; it's the soul he coaxes from a piece of spruce, a tangible legacy in the heart of a digital city."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was fourteen, huddled by the radiator in his Leningrad flat. His friend Sasha had smuggled it in\u2014a cassette of *Abbey Road*. Through the hiss of the cheap player, the harmonies felt like a forbidden architecture of emotion. Tracing the grain on the wooden table, Ivan understood for the first time that wood and wire could be assembled into something that felt more real than the concrete world outside. It was a secret language he knew he had to learn, a seed of warmth planted in the Soviet cold.\n(Late 1980s)\n\n2.\nAt the Oregon community college, a classmate brought him her guitar, its neck snapped clean. Everyone saw firewood; Ivan saw a broken throat. He worked for two days, his hands remembering a patience he didn't know he had. When he handed it back, newly strung, she played a hesitant chord. The sound filled the workshop, alive and whole again. In that moment of resonance, he felt he hadn't just fixed an object, but restored a voice. His life's purpose became clear, sharp as a chisel.\n(Mid-1990s)\n\n3.\nMonths into his apprenticeship, the old Portland luthier had barely spoken to him. Then one morning, the man silently placed a plank of stiff, pale Sitka spruce on Ivan\u2019s bench. \"The story is already in it,\" the old man rasped, tapping the wood. \"Your job is not to tell a new one, but to let this one be heard.\" It wasn\u2019t a lesson in woodworking; it was a transfer of philosophy. Ivan learned then that his role was not to be a creator, but a translator for the wood.\n(Late 1990s)\n\n4.\nHe remembers the specific quality of the light that afternoon in the Mission. He\u2019d biked past the dusty little storefront a dozen times, but today the sun hit the grimy glass just so, illuminating the empty space within. It wasn't a calculation; it was a physical pull, a feeling of recognition. This was it. This was the sanctuary. In a city that moved at digital speed, he had found a quiet, analog corner to house his life\u2019s work. He felt, perhaps for the first time since leaving home, truly anchored.\n(Early 2000s)\n\n5.\nStanding in the back of The Chapel last year, he watched a local songwriter cradle one of his earliest Petrov guitars. He knew every millimeter of that instrument\u2014the slight imperfection in the rosette, the specific resonance of its braced Adirondack top. When she sang a mournful ballad, the guitar\u2019s voice was the other half of her own: warm, clear, and full of sorrowful beauty. He felt no pride of ownership, only the profound, quiet satisfaction of having built a vessel worthy of the song. His work was complete.\n(2022)"
